</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-42_ pf-text-1">The Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 and the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 outline employers' legal obligations to ensure their staff's health, safety, and well-being, including support workers.
























































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-44_ pf-text-1">Best practice guidelines from professional bodies such as the Royal College of Nursing (RCN) and the British Association of Social Workers (BASW) provide valuable insights into effective support worker training strategies. They emphasise the importance of continuous professional development (CPD) and person-centred care approaches.

























































</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-46_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-47_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-48_ pf-heading-1-h3">Understanding the support worker role</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-50_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Support workers are pivotal in delivering high-quality care across various healthcare and social care settings. Their responsibilities encompass a wide range of tasks to support individuals to live as independently as possible while maintaining their dignity and autonomy.






 

  
<br>
